at Last? The Fate of Ulrich Müther’s Magdeburg Hypar Shell in a Changing Society -- tThe Music Pavilion in Sassnitz. A Shell Structure by Ulrich Müther in Collaboration with Dietmar Kuntzsch and Otto Patzelt -- tUlrich Müther: Quantity or Quality? -- tZusammenfassungen -- tResúmenes -- tAcknowledgments -- tPicture Credits -- tIndices0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aConcrete shell construction started to become popular in the mid-20th century. Technically advanced designs with conspicuous expressiveness began to appear all over the world. With three typical protagonists – Félix Candela (1910–1997), Heinz Isler (1926–2009), and Ulrich Müther (1934–2007) – the book examines this construction method. Their work – primarily in Mexico, Switzerland, and the former GDR – was carried out under very different political, economic, social, and cultural conditions. The authors analyze the buildings and projects against the background of developments in architecture and engineering at that time. The focus is on mutual influence, shared aspects and differences in the design processes, the structural design, and the execution. In addition, the book examines how the work was received and today’s application of the building method.  aMitte des 20. Jahrhunderts begann die Hochphase des Betonschalenbaus. Weltweit entstanden technisch avancierte Konstruktionen von aufsehenerregender Expressivität. Mit Félix Candela, Heinz Isler und Ulrich Müther nimmt dieses Buch exemplarisch drei Protagonisten dieser Bauweise in den Blick. Ihr Wirken – vorwiegend in Mexiko, der Schweiz und der DDR – fand unter sehr verschiedenen politischen, ökonomisch-sozialen und kulturellen Bedingungen statt. Die Autoren analysieren die Bauten und Projekte vor dem Hintergrund der Entwicklungen der Architektur und des Ingenieurwesens jener Zeit. Sie thematisieren wechselseitige Einflüsse, Gemeinsamkeiten wie Unterschiede in den Entwurfsprozessen, der Konstruktion und der Ausführung. Darüber hinaus werden Fragen der Rezeption und der heutigen Nutzung behandelt.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aArchitecture, Moderny20th centuryxThemes, motives. 0aArchitecture, Moderny21st centuryxThemes, motives. 0aReinforced concrete construction. 0aShells, Concrete. 7aARCHITECTURE / Methods & Materials.2bisacsh1 aAlarcón Azuela, Eduardo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeckh, Matthias, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoller, Giulia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrorson, Susanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChilton, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDechau, Wilfried, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGenzel, Elke, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGiebeler, Georg, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGonzález Pendás, María, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIgnacio Del Cueto Ruiz-Funes, Juan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLudwig, Matthias, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aLudwig, Matthias, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMendoza, Marisela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOliva Salinas, Juan Gerardo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchätzke, Andreas, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aSchätzke, Andreas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchützeichel, Rainer, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/r